## Referencing other Blocks with `$ref`

Some Block types compose other Blocks. For example, an `s3-bucket` Block holds
a reference to an `aws-credentials` Block, and a `dbt-core-operation` Block
holds a reference to a `dbt-cli-profile` Block. Rather than inlining the
referenced Block's data, the API expects a `$ref` expression that points at
the referenced Block document by ID:

```hcl
data = jsonencode({
  "credentials" = { "$ref" = { "block_document_id" = prefect_block.creds.id } }
})
```

You can use `prefect block type inspect <slug>` to confirm when a field
expects a `$ref`. For example, the following screenshot shows the output of
`prefect block type inspect dbt-core-operation`:

<img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/PrefectHQ/terraform-provider-prefect/main/docs/images/block-type-inspect-ref-key.png" alt="Block type inspect ref key" align="center" width="400">

For more information on the `$ref` syntax definition, see the
[dollarref's specification in the JSON schema](https://json-schema.org/understanding-json-schema/structuring#dollarref).

**Drift detection is skipped for Blocks whose `data` contains a `$ref`.** The
API resolves `$ref` server-side and returns the resolved nested data, which
would never match the literal HCL. Out-of-band edits to a `$ref`-using Block
will not surface as drift on the next plan; manage these Blocks carefully.

